        "dean": "Dean"
    },
    {
        " , but also as abbot .     When the great reform of the 11th century had put an end to the direct jurisdiction of the lay abbots, the honorary title of abbot continued to be held by certain of the great feudal families, as late as the 13th century and later, with the head of the community retaining the title of dean. The connection of the lesser lay abbots with the abbeys, especially in the south of France, lasted longer; and certain feudal families retained the title of   for centuries, together with certain rights over the abbey lands or revenues. The abuse was not confined to the West. John, ": null
